## Refined Setup (Incorporating Everything)

### One-time setup

```bash
# 1. Create sandbox user
# System Settings → Users & Groups → Add user: llm-test (Standard)

# 2. Enable SSH
sudo systemsetup -setremotelogin on

# 3. Harden SSH configuration
sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config

# Add or ensure these lines:
AllowUsers llm-test
PasswordAuthentication no

# 4. Set up SSH key authentication for llm-test
# Then reload SSH:
sudo launchctl stop com.openssh.sshd
sudo launchctl start com.openssh.sshd

# 5. Add alias to main user
echo 'alias llm="ssh llm-test@localhost"' >> ~/.zshrc
```

### Inside the SSH session (llm-test)

```bash
# Auto-enter sandbox on login
echo 'cd ~/llm-sandbox' >> ~/.zshrc

# Panic reset — actually cleans everything including hidden files
echo 'alias llm-nuke="find ~/llm-sandbox -mindepth 1 -delete"' >> ~/.zshrc

# Guardrail function
cat << 'EOF' >> ~/.zshrc
function safe-run() {
  if [[ "$PWD" != $HOME/llm-sandbox* ]]; then
    echo "❌ Not in sandbox. Aborting."
    return 1
  fi
  "$@"
}
EOF
```

### Daily workflow

```bash
# Normal experimentation
llm                    # SSH into llm-test
mkdir exp-$(date +%s) && cd $_
python3 -m venv venv && source venv/bin/activate
# ... do work ...
deactivate && cd .. && rm -rf exp-*

# Panic
llm-nuke               # back to clean slate
```

### Escalation path

| Risk level | Action |
|------------|--------|
| Trusted tools, known code | Main user, sandbox dir |
| Unknown repo, agent/tooling | `llm` → SSH into llm-test |
| **Anything that modifies the system or runs untrusted code with side effects** | VM |
| Maximum paranoia | Air-gapped VM |

That "system modification" trigger is the real dividing line people miss. If it touches `brew`, `pip` outside a venv, modifies dotfiles (`~/.zshrc`, `~/.bashrc`, etc.), or changes anything outside the sandbox → VM.

